# Stacklite - Freelancer OS
A Next.js + Supabase freelancer workspace with five core modules: Client Manager, Time Tracker, Contract Generator, Invoice Generator, and Income Tracker.

## Current State
- Auth: Supabase Auth (email/password + social), callback routes, protected dashboard
- Client Manager: Full CRUD with search, persisted to Supabase
- Time Tracker: Running timers, manual entries, pause/resume/stop, edit support
- Contract Generator: Guest + auth flows, PDF export, share-token routes
- Invoice Generator: Guest + auth flows, itemized totals, payment status, share-token routes
- Income Tracker: Data-driven from invoice/client data, period-based insights
- Guest mode: Zustand persist with guest-aware hooks (localStorage ↔ Supabase switching)

## Tech Stack
- Framework: Next.js 16 (App Router)
- Runtime: React 19
- Language: TypeScript (strict mode)
- Styling: Tailwind CSS v4
- Database: Supabase SSR + Supabase JS
- Data Fetching: React Query
- State: Zustand (with persist)
- Validation: Zod
- Testing: Vitest

## Design System: Lumea Token Architecture

### Typography
- Primary Font: Satoshi (titles AND body — no Inter)
- Variable: --font-sans in app/globals.css
- Tailwind mapping: fontFamily.sans
- Roles:
  - Page title: prominent, semibold, high contrast
  - Section heading: concise, stable across modules
  - Body: readable line length, moderate contrast
  - Helper/meta: subdued with text-text-muted
  - Labels/errors: compact, context-bound

### Color Token System (CRITICAL)
**Never use raw hex or Tailwind default palette classes.**
Always use semantic Lumea utilities defined in tailwind.config.ts.

Token categories:
1. Canvas/Page: bg-page, bg-canvas, bg-background-base, bg-background-highlight, bg-background-muted
2. Text: text-text-base, text-text-body, text-text-muted, text-text-placeholder, text-text-disabled, text-text-brand
3. Borders: border-border-base, border-border-muted, border-border-input, border-border-disabled, border-border-brand
4. Buttons:
   - Primary: bg-button-primary text-button-primary-fg
   - Secondary: bg-button-secondary text-button-secondary-fg
   - Ghost: text-button-ghost-fg
5. Feedback:
   - Error: text-feedback-error-text, bg-feedback-error-bg, border-feedback-error-border
   - Success: text-feedback-success-text, bg-feedback-success-bg, border-feedback-success-border
   - Warning: text-feedback-warning-text, bg-feedback-warning-bg, border-feedback-warning-border
   - Info: text-feedback-info-text, bg-feedback-info-bg, border-feedback-info-border
6. Brand: text-brand-*, bg-brand-*, border-brand-*
7. Specialized: icon.*, topbar.*, module.*, dock.*, step.*, badge.*, preview.*

### Spacing Scale (4px grid system)
Token aliases: xs, sm, md, lg, xl, 2xl, 3xl, 4xl
Use consistent 4px-increment rhythm in layouts.

### Shape Tokens
- Radius: rounded-sm (tight), rounded-md (inputs), rounded-lg (buttons), rounded-xl (cards/panels)
- Shadows: shadow-sm (inline fields), shadow-md (cards), shadow-lg (modals/floating)

### Focus Ring Contract (NON-NEGOTIABLE)
Every interactive control MUST have:
- focus-visible:ring-2
- focus-visible:ring-text-brand (or semantic ring token)
- Appropriate ring offset on layered surfaces

### Global Utility Classes
Available helpers:
- canvas-grid, dots-background
- theme-page-shell
- theme-shell-card, theme-shell-panel, theme-shell-divider, theme-shell-chip, theme-shell-chip-strong
- theme-shell-muted, theme-shell-subtle, theme-shell-strong
- theme-shell-field
- theme-scrollbar

### Motion Tokens
- animate-fade-in / animate-fadeIn
- animate-slide-in / animate-slideIn
- skeleton shimmer for loading states
Rules: Motion indicates state change, not decoration. Keep durations subtle and brief.

## Architecture Patterns

### Project Structure
app/                         App Router routes and layouts
├── (auth)/                  Auth route group
├── (dashboard)/             Protected dashboard routes
├── auth/                    Auth handlers (callback, signout, delete-account)
├── c/[token]/              Contract share view
├── i/[token]/              Invoice share view
├── globals.css             CSS custom properties (token source)
└── layout.tsx              Root layout

components/
├── ui/                      Primitives (Button, Input, Card, Modal, etc.)
├── workspace/              Canvas, ModuleCard, Dock, Navbar
├── layout/                 AppNavbar, GuestIndicator, SavePromptModal, SignInButton
└── modules/                ClientManager, TimeTracker, ContractGenerator, InvoiceGenerator, IncomeTracker

hooks/                       React Query and app hooks
lib/                         API, validation, types, utilities, Supabase clients, navigation registries (e.g. workspaceModules)
stores/                      Zustand stores (guest-aware)
supabase/migrations/         Database schema and migrations
tests/                       Unit tests (Vitest)
docs/                        Product and implementation docs (includes architecture-standards.md)

### Cross-cutting architecture (scalability)

- **Canonical workspace modules** — IDs, `?module=` deep links, and landing card copy for modules live in `lib/navigation/workspaceModules.ts`. Do not duplicate module id lists or hand-build `/dashboard?module=` strings in multiple files; import helpers from that module.
- **Layering** — Keep Supabase and heavy validation in `lib/` + `hooks/`; routes and `components/modules` compose UI and call hooks. Avoid embedding new API clients inside large UI files.
- **Authoritative doc** — See `docs/architecture-standards.md` for layering rules, quality gates, and how to add features without one-offs.

### Component Composition Rules
1. Reuse primitives from components/ui before creating module-specific controls
2. Keep visual rhythm consistent across all modules
3. Every module MUST include: empty, loading, error, and success states
4. Destructive actions require explicit confirmation UI

### Naming Conventions
- Components: PascalCase (ClientCard.tsx)
- Utilities: camelCase (formatCurrency.ts)
- Types: PascalCase with T prefix (TClient, TInvoice, TContract)
- Hooks: use prefix (useClients.ts, useTimers.ts)
- Stores: use prefix (useClientStore.ts, useGuestStore.ts)
- Constants: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE

## TypeScript Standards

### Strict Mode Requirements
- No any types (use unknown or proper typing)
- Interfaces for object shapes, Types for unions/primitives
- Props interfaces: suffix with Props (ClientCardProps)
- All functions: explicit return type annotations
- Null checks: strict null checking enabled

### Type Organization
```typescript
// Export types from dedicated files
// lib/types/client.ts
export type TClient = {
id: string;
name: string;
email: string | null;
company: string | null;
created_at: string;
updated_at: string;
};export type TClientFormData = Omit<TClient, 'id' | 'created_at' | 'updated_at'>;

## React Patterns

### Server vs Client Components
- Server Components by default (no 'use client' unless needed)
- Client Components only for: interactivity, state, effects, browser APIs
- Keep Server Components for: static content, data fetching, layouts

### Component Structure Template
```typescript// Server Component (default)
import { ComponentProps } from './types';export function ComponentName({ prop }: ComponentProps) {
return <div>...</div>;
}// Client Component (when needed)
'use client';import { useState } from 'react';
import { ComponentProps } from './types';export function InteractiveComponent({ prop }: ComponentProps) {
const [state, setState] = useState();
return <div>...</div>;
}

### Custom Hooks
- Prefix with 'use'
- Extract shared logic from components
- Keep single responsibility
- Return stable references (useMemo, useCallback where needed)

## State Management

### Zustand Store Pattern
```typescriptimport { create } from 'zustand';
import { persist } from 'zustand/middleware';interface TFeatureStore {
items: TItem[];
loading: boolean;
error: string | null;
// Actions
setItems: (items: TItem[]) => void;
addItem: (item: TItem) => void;
updateItem: (id: string, updates: Partial<TItem>) => void;
removeItem: (id: string) => void;
}export const useFeatureStore = create<TFeatureStore>()(
persist(
(set) => ({
items: [],
loading: false,
error: null,
setItems: (items) => set({ items }),
addItem: (item) => set((state) => ({
items: [...state.items, item]
})),
updateItem: (id, updates) => set((state) => ({
items: state.items.map(item =>
item.id === id ? { ...item, ...updates } : item
)
})),
removeItem: (id) => set((state) => ({
items: state.items.filter(item => item.id !== id)
}))
}),
{ name: 'feature-storage' }
)
);

### Guest-Aware Hook Pattern
```typescript// hooks/useClients.ts
import { useAuth } from './useAuth';
import { useGuestStore } from '@/stores/useGuestStore';
import { useQuery } from '@tanstack/react-query';export function useClients() {
const { user } = useAuth();
const guestClients = useGuestStore(state => state.clients);const { data: supabaseClients } = useQuery({
queryKey: ['clients', user?.id],
queryFn: fetchClientsFromSupabase,
enabled: !!user
});return user ? supabaseClients : guestClients;
}

## Supabase Integration

### Client Usage
```typescript// Server-side data fetching
import { createClient } from '@/lib/supabase/server';export async function getClients() {
const supabase = await createClient();
const { data, error } = await supabase
.from('clients')
.select('*')
.order('created_at', { ascending: false });if (error) throw error;
return data;
}// Client-side auth/mutations
import { createClient } from '@/lib/supabase/client';const supabase = createClient();
await supabase.auth.signInWithPassword({ email, password });

### RLS Requirements
- ALL user-isolated tables MUST have RLS enabled
- Policies must enforce user_id matching auth.uid()
- Share-token routes use public read policies with token validation
- Never expose service-role key to client code

### Migration Order (CRITICAL)
Apply in exact sequence:
1. 20260212000000_initial_schema.sql
2. 20260214000000_extend_clients_profile.sql
3. 20260401000000_extend_contracts.sql
4. 20260403000000_backfill_share_tokens.sql
5. 20260404000000_invoices_clean.sql
6. 20260406000000_cookie_consents.sql

## Validation with Zod

### Form Validation Pattern
```typescriptimport { z } from 'zod';export const clientSchema = z.object({
name: z.string().min(1, 'Name is required'),
email: z.string().email('Invalid email').nullable(),
company: z.string().nullable(),
});export type TClientFormData = z.infer<typeof clientSchema>;// In component
const { register, handleSubmit, formState: { errors } } = useForm<TClientFormData>({
resolver: zodResolver(clientSchema)
});

